english:
  title: Four Verses on the Yunbrocade Tower, in Response to Lee Myeong-suk
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I. Lotus Marsh in Moonlight

    Gentle ripples lap the shore as moonlight melts and flows,
    A single breeze moves through ten acres of lotus blooms.
    I remember sleeping at the foot of Linping Mountain—
    When I woke from wine, my body floated in a painted boat.

    II. Pine Valley, Jade Clouds

    The whole forest's golden leaves drift far in soundless air,
    While azure clouds in every ravine swell and rise.
    Swept up the mountainside, they cannot scatter or disperse—
    It seems the evening rain has never fully cleared.

    III. Fisherman's Ledge at Dusk

    Young fish emerge to play among the ripples,
    As I cast my slender line into the willow's shade.
    When sunset comes and I turn homeward,
    My clothes are half-drenched, and green mist mingles with rain to darken the hills ahead.

    IV. Mountain Lodge at Dawn

    Whose house is that below the mountain, looking far like a village?
    Smoke from the roof is a sign of peaceful times.
    Now and then a dog barks at the crumbling fence,
    And someone comes to knock, asking for a flame to light.
  footnotes:
    - Linping Mountain (臨平) is a famous site in Zhejiang Province, China, known for its scenic beauty and historical associations.
    - These four verses follow the traditional Chinese poetic form of parallel quatrains, each painting a distinct seasonal or diurnal landscape scene.
    - The work demonstrates the poet's mastery of the regulated verse form while capturing intimate moments of natural observation and reflection.
